{
  "id": "idiampro-operations-2026",
  "name": "IdiamPro - Operations",
  "rootNodeId": "root-ops",
  "nodes": {
    "root-ops": {
      "id": "root-ops",
      "name": "IdiamPro - Operations",
      "content": "<p><strong>Operational Runbook for IdiamPro</strong></p><p>This is the back-office playbook for running IdiamPro day-to-day: how applicants get onboarded, how users get supported, how bugs get triaged, how emails go out, how money flows in and out, how strategic partnerships get tracked, how incidents get handled, and how compliance requests get processed.</p><p>Written for the founder (and any future operations hire) to follow without guessing. When in doubt, the runbook trumps the impulse.</p><p><em>Created: 2026-06-11</em></p>",
      "type": "root",
      "parentId": null,
      "childrenIds": [
        "ops-beta-program",
        "ops-user-support",
        "ops-bug-intake",
        "ops-email-comms",
        "ops-financial",
        "ops-partnerships",
        "ops-incident-response",
        "ops-compliance-privacy",
        "ops-env-vars-vercel-ref-2026-06-12"
      ],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": ""
    },
    "ops-beta-program": {
      "id": "ops-beta-program",
      "name": "Beta Program Operations",
      "content": "<p>How beta applicants get from the application form to active testers to founding-user testimonial sources.</p>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "root-ops",
      "childrenIds": [
        "beta-intake-workflow",
        "beta-approval-process",
        "beta-feedback-followup",
        "beta-founding-badge",
        "beta-crosslink-bizdev"
      ],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "1"
    },
    "beta-intake-workflow": {
      "id": "beta-intake-workflow",
      "name": "Applicant Intake Workflow",
      "content": "<p>Beta applications land in the database from the public beta sign-up form on the marketing site. The admin review surface for them is the <strong>/admin/applicants</strong> page in-app.</p><p><strong>Daily cadence:</strong> Open /admin/applicants once a day. New applicants appear at the top.</p><p><strong>Each application shows:</strong> name, email, intended use case, why-they-want-it free-text, sign-up date.</p><p><strong>What to look for:</strong> writers, students, researchers, knowledge workers \u2014 the primary segments. Applicants who describe a clear use case get prioritized. Vague applications (\"sounds cool\") go to the back of the queue, not the trash.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-beta-program",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "1.1"
    },
    "beta-approval-process": {
      "id": "beta-approval-process",
      "name": "Approval Process",
      "content": "<p>Approval is a single click on the /admin/applicants row.</p><p><strong>What happens when you click Approve:</strong></p><ul><li>Applicant record is marked approved.</li><li>The system queues an onboarding welcome email to the applicant.</li><li>The applicant's Clerk account is provisioned with beta access flags.</li><li>The applicant moves out of the pending queue.</li></ul><p><strong>Howard makes the call.</strong> No automated approval. The judgment call is whether this person will use the app and give useful feedback, not whether they pass a checklist.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-beta-program",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "1.2"
    },
    "beta-feedback-followup": {
      "id": "beta-feedback-followup",
      "name": "Feedback Follow-up",
      "content": "<p>Two paths for soliciting feedback from beta users.</p><p><strong>Automated 14-day cron.</strong> Fourteen days after approval, the system sends a templated feedback request asking what's working, what's broken, what's missing. Replies come back to support@2ndbrainware.com.</p><p><strong>Manual outreach via /admin/feedback.</strong> When a beta user submits unprompted feedback through the in-app form, it lands in /admin/feedback. High-quality feedback (specific, articulate, enthusiastic) gets flagged for a personal follow-up: would they be willing to do a short video testimonial? Howard sends those personally.</p><p><strong>Cadence:</strong> Review /admin/feedback every business day. Reply within 24 hours.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-beta-program",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "1.3"
    },
    "beta-founding-badge": {
      "id": "beta-founding-badge",
      "name": "Founding User Badge Issuance",
      "content": "<p>Beta users who record a video testimonial earn the <strong>Founding User</strong> badge on their profile. This is permanent recognition \u2014 the badge stays even after the beta program ends.</p><p><strong>Trigger:</strong> Howard receives a usable video testimonial (clear audio, names IdiamPro, describes specific value).</p><p><strong>Action:</strong> Flip the founding-user flag on the user record. The badge renders automatically in their account UI.</p><p><strong>Why it matters:</strong> Beta users gave us their time and their words before there was social proof to point to. The badge is the public acknowledgment, and a soft retention lever \u2014 Founding User churn-out is more painful than regular churn, so they tend to stay.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-beta-program",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "1.4"
    },
    "beta-crosslink-bizdev": {
      "id": "beta-crosslink-bizdev",
      "name": "Customer Segments (BizDev \u2014 Authors)",
      "content": "",
      "type": "outline-link",
      "parentId": "ops-beta-program",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": "1.5",
      "linkedOutlineId": "biz-dev-2026"
    },
    "ops-user-support": {
      "id": "ops-user-support",
      "name": "User Support",
      "content": "<p>How user-reported issues get triaged and resolved.</p>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "root-ops",
      "childrenIds": [
        "support-intake",
        "support-sla",
        "support-refund-ref",
        "support-categories",
        "support-escalation"
      ],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "2"
    },
    "support-intake": {
      "id": "support-intake",
      "name": "Intake Channels",
      "content": "<p>Users reach support through two channels.</p><p><strong>Email: support@2ndbrainware.com</strong> \u2014 primary channel. (Mailbox creation is still pending \u2014 see Bootstrap Plan. Until that mailbox is live, support replies route through Howard's personal address with a planned cutover.)</p><p><strong>In-app feedback form.</strong> A user can hit Help \u2192 Send Feedback from anywhere in the app. Submissions land in /admin/feedback alongside beta feedback.</p><p><strong>No phone, no chat widget</strong> in v1. Both channels are async on purpose \u2014 they let Howard batch responses instead of getting interrupt-driven.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-user-support",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "2.1"
    },
    "support-sla": {
      "id": "support-sla",
      "name": "Response SLA",
      "content": "<p><strong>Initial reply:</strong> within 24 business hours. Acknowledge that we heard them. Even if the answer is \"we're looking into it,\" reply same-day.</p><p><strong>Resolution target:</strong> 72 hours for non-critical issues. Critical issues (data loss, account locked out, billing wrong) bump to P0 and get handled same-day.</p><p><strong>Off-hours:</strong> Howard does not commit to weekend or evening responses in v1. The 24-hour SLA is measured in business hours, not wall-clock hours. This will need to change as the user base grows.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-user-support",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "2.2"
    },
    "support-refund-ref": {
      "id": "support-refund-ref",
      "name": "Refund Policy Reference (Legal)",
      "content": "",
      "type": "outline-link",
      "parentId": "ops-user-support",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": "2.3",
      "linkedOutlineId": "idiampro-legal-compliance"
    },
    "support-categories": {
      "id": "support-categories",
      "name": "Common Support Categories",
      "content": "<p>Most support tickets fall into one of five buckets. Categorize on first reply so we can see patterns.</p><ul><li><strong>Account access</strong> \u2014 login failures, password resets, Clerk verification issues.</li><li><strong>Billing</strong> \u2014 subscription changes, refund requests, double-charges, Stripe/RevenueCat reconciliation.</li><li><strong>AI errors</strong> \u2014 Gemini timeouts, BYOK key rejected, transform produced bad output, model unavailable.</li><li><strong>Sync issues</strong> \u2014 outline didn't appear on another device, file lost, conflict resolution confusion.</li><li><strong>Feature questions</strong> \u2014 \"how do I do X?\" \u2014 answer briefly and link to the User Guide section.</li></ul><p>Track the running tally; when one category spikes, that's a signal that a fix or a doc update is overdue.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-user-support",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "2.4"
    },
    "support-escalation": {
      "id": "support-escalation",
      "name": "Escalation Criteria",
      "content": "<p>Most tickets are handled directly. Escalation is reserved for these triggers:</p><ul><li><strong>Data loss reported.</strong> Even a single user reporting a missing outline goes to incident response.</li><li><strong>Legal threat or regulator inquiry.</strong> Stop replying and route to counsel.</li><li><strong>Press inquiry.</strong> Route to Howard personally; do not improvise.</li><li><strong>Refund dispute above $100.</strong> Howard approves personally.</li><li><strong>Repeated complaints from the same user.</strong> Pattern signals; escalate for direct outreach.</li></ul>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-user-support",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "2.5"
    },
    "ops-bug-intake": {
      "id": "ops-bug-intake",
      "name": "Bug Intake",
      "content": "<p>How user-reported bugs, internal QA finds, and Playwright failures get captured, triaged, and resolved.</p>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "root-ops",
      "childrenIds": [
        "bug-crosslink-buglog",
        "bug-severity",
        "bug-triage-cadence",
        "bug-fix-verification"
      ],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "3"
    },
    "bug-crosslink-buglog": {
      "id": "bug-crosslink-buglog",
      "name": "IdiamPro - Bug Log",
      "content": "",
      "type": "outline-link",
      "parentId": "ops-bug-intake",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": "3.1",
      "linkedOutlineId": "idiampro-bug-log-2026"
    },
    "bug-severity": {
      "id": "bug-severity",
      "name": "Severity Assignment",
      "content": "<p>Every bug gets a severity tag on intake. The tag determines the queue it lives in and the urgency of the fix.</p><ul><li><strong>P0 \u2014 Launch blocker / data loss / app crash.</strong> Drop everything. Reproduce, fix, ship within 24 hours.</li><li><strong>P1 \u2014 Feature broken.</strong> A documented feature does not work as described. Fix within the current week.</li><li><strong>P2 \u2014 Polish.</strong> Visual glitch, awkward copy, edge-case behavior. Batch into the next release.</li><li><strong>P3 \u2014 Nice-to-have.</strong> Quality-of-life improvement that no one's complained about. Backlog.</li></ul><p>When in doubt, severity bumps up, not down. A P1 that turned out to be a P2 wastes a day; a P2 that was actually a P0 loses a user.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-bug-intake",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "3.2"
    },
    "bug-triage-cadence": {
      "id": "bug-triage-cadence",
      "name": "Triage Cadence",
      "content": "<p><strong>Daily review</strong> of newly captured bugs. Open the Bug Log outline, look at any node added since yesterday, assign severity, and either fix immediately (P0/P1) or move it to the right bucket.</p><p><strong>Weekly sweep.</strong> Once a week, walk the P2 and P3 lists and either promote, resolve, or close as won't-fix.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-bug-intake",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "3.3"
    },
    "bug-fix-verification": {
      "id": "bug-fix-verification",
      "name": "Fix Verification Flow",
      "content": "<p>The same flow applies to every bug regardless of severity.</p><ol><li><strong>Reproduce.</strong> Confirm the bug exists before touching code. If it can't be reproduced, ask the reporter for steps.</li><li><strong>Write a failing test.</strong> Playwright when the bug touches the UI; unit test when it's pure logic.</li><li><strong>Fix.</strong></li><li><strong>Re-test.</strong> Run the test, then drive the original repro by hand to confirm the user-facing experience is right.</li><li><strong>Mark verified.</strong> Move the bug node to Resolved Bugs in the Bug Log, with the fix commit hash in the content.</li></ol><p>Skipping the failing-test step is the single biggest contributor to regression. Don't skip it.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-bug-intake",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "3.4"
    },
    "ops-email-comms": {
      "id": "ops-email-comms",
      "name": "Email Communications",
      "content": "<p>How transactional and lifecycle emails go out, and where the templates live.</p>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "root-ops",
      "childrenIds": [
        "email-plain-english-refresher-2026-06-11",
        "email-onboarding-drip",
        "email-templates-location",
        "email-send-infra",
        "email-unsubscribe"
      ],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "4"
    },
    "email-plain-english-refresher-2026-06-11": {
      "id": "email-plain-english-refresher-2026-06-11",
      "name": "Plain-English Refresher: How Email Plumbing Works",
      "content": "<p><strong>How the email system works (plain English):</strong></p><p><strong>The five pieces:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>2ndbrainware.com</strong> \u2014 your domain name. The street address of your business on the internet.</li><li><strong>Namecheap</strong> \u2014 where you bought the domain. Also where you control its \"phone book\" \u2014 the DNS \u2014 which tells the rest of the world where your website lives and where your email lives.</li><li><strong>Vercel</strong> \u2014 the company that runs your website's computers. When someone types 2ndbrainware.com, Vercel hands them the page.</li><li><strong>PrivateEmail</strong> \u2014 your business mailbox. Think of it as a P.O. box at Namecheap that receives mail addressed to howard@2ndbrainware.com.</li><li><strong>Upstash</strong> \u2014 a tiny database that remembers who applied to your beta. Like a notebook that's always synced.</li></ul><p><strong>What happens when someone signs up:</strong></p><ol><li>They visit <strong>2ndbrainware.com</strong> in their browser. Vercel sends them the marketing page.</li><li>They fill out the signup form (name, email, \"what brings you here\") and click submit.</li><li>A small program on Vercel catches the form data. It does two things in order: writes the applicant's name and email into <strong>Upstash</strong> (so you have a permanent record), then it tells <strong>PrivateEmail</strong> (through a behind-the-scenes service called SMTP \u2014 basically the email pipeline) to send YOU a notification email.</li><li>PrivateEmail delivers the email to <strong>howard@2ndbrainware.com</strong>. It arrives in your mailbox within seconds.</li><li>You open the mailbox (via the webmail shortcut on your Desktop) and see who applied.</li></ol><p><strong>The same pieces handle approval too:</strong> when you click \"Approve\" in the admin dashboard, Vercel asks PrivateEmail to send the new user a \"welcome to the beta\" email. Same path.</p><p>Five companies, three for the website + one for the mailbox + one for the database. Each does one thing.</p><p><strong>Set up 2026-06-11</strong> during a single working session including: pointing 2ndbrainware.com DNS at Vercel, configuring PrivateEmail MX records via Namecheap's MAIL SETTINGS, provisioning Upstash KV in Vercel's Storage tab, swapping the email sender from Resend to PrivateEmail SMTP via nodemailer, and migrating file-based JSON storage to Upstash KV.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-email-comms",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "4.0"
    },
    "email-onboarding-drip": {
      "id": "email-onboarding-drip",
      "name": "Onboarding Drip Schedule",
      "content": "<p>Four touches in the first two weeks after approval.</p><ul><li><strong>Day 0 \u2014 Welcome.</strong> Account active, here's how to start, link to the User Guide.</li><li><strong>Day 3 \u2014 Tips.</strong> Three small wins (keyboard shortcuts, the AI sparkle button, drag-reorder).</li><li><strong>Day 7 \u2014 Power user features.</strong> Smart Tools, Refresh from Web, derivative outlines, image-to-outline. \"Did you know IdiamPro can\u2026\"</li><li><strong>Day 14 \u2014 Feedback ask.</strong> What's working? What isn't? Would you do a short video testimonial?</li></ul><p>If the user has clearly stopped using the app (no sessions in 7+ days), the Day 14 email is replaced with a re-engagement nudge instead of a feedback ask.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-email-comms",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "4.1"
    },
    "email-templates-location": {
      "id": "email-templates-location",
      "name": "Templates Location",
      "content": "<p>Email templates live alongside the rest of the codebase. <strong>Action item for the operations review:</strong> find the exact directory and list it here. Likely candidates are <code>src/lib/email/</code>, <code>src/emails/</code>, or wherever Resend templates are registered. Update this node with the path once confirmed.</p><p>The templates are owned by Howard and reviewed before any drip schedule change. Wording matters disproportionately \u2014 every drip email is read by every new user.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-email-comms",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "4.2"
    },
    "email-send-infra": {
      "id": "email-send-infra",
      "name": "Send Infrastructure",
      "content": "<p><strong>Provider: Resend.</strong> Transactional and lifecycle emails go through Resend. The API key lives in environment variables, gated so missing keys silently disable sending instead of erroring.</p><p><strong>Triggers.</strong> Drip emails are kicked off by cron jobs that scan user records for due touches. Transactional emails (welcome, password reset, billing receipts) fire on the in-app event.</p><p><strong>Monitoring.</strong> Resend's dashboard shows delivery rate and bounces. Anything below 95% deliverability is investigated.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-email-comms",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "4.3"
    },
    "email-unsubscribe": {
      "id": "email-unsubscribe",
      "name": "Unsubscribe Handling",
      "content": "<p>Every lifecycle email includes a one-click unsubscribe link. Unsubscribing flips a flag on the user record that suppresses all future non-transactional emails.</p><p><strong>What still goes through:</strong> billing receipts, password resets, account-security notices, legal notices. Unsubscribe applies to marketing and lifecycle touches only.</p><p><strong>CAN-SPAM and GDPR compliance.</strong> Honor the unsubscribe within 10 business days (we do it instantly). The mechanism cannot require login or a password.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-email-comms",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "4.4"
    },
    "ops-financial": {
      "id": "ops-financial",
      "name": "Financial Operations",
      "content": "<p>How money moves in and out of the business, and the cadence for watching it.</p>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "root-ops",
      "childrenIds": [
        "fin-revenue-tracking",
        "fin-cost-monitoring",
        "fin-beta-impact",
        "fin-reconciliation"
      ],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "5"
    },
    "fin-revenue-tracking": {
      "id": "fin-revenue-tracking",
      "name": "Revenue Tracking",
      "content": "<p>Two dashboards.</p><ul><li><strong>Stripe</strong> \u2014 web subscriptions (Student and Pro tiers via the Stripe checkout flow). Daily MRR, new vs. churned subscribers, failed charges.</li><li><strong>RevenueCat</strong> \u2014 iOS subscriptions (App Store in-app purchases). Same metrics, but funneled through Apple's payment system.</li></ul><p>The two dashboards do not auto-merge. Monthly reconciliation pulls both into a single revenue snapshot. Watch for the gap between Stripe revenue and RevenueCat revenue \u2014 that ratio tells us where new users are coming from.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-financial",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "5.1"
    },
    "fin-cost-monitoring": {
      "id": "fin-cost-monitoring",
      "name": "Cost Monitoring",
      "content": "<p>Three buckets of recurring cost.</p><ul><li><strong>AI API spend.</strong> Gemini (today), Claude (when partnership lands), video AI tools per-user (Runway, MagicLight, etc. \u2014 see Strategic Partnerships). Check each provider dashboard weekly. Any spike >2\u00d7 the rolling 7-day average gets investigated.</li><li><strong>Hosting.</strong> Vercel (web), App Store fees (iOS), Supabase/Postgres or equivalent for any server-side data.</li><li><strong>Email.</strong> Resend monthly subscription based on volume tier.</li></ul><p>Cost per active user is the headline number. As long as it sits below subscription revenue per active user, the unit economics work.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-financial",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "5.2"
    },
    "fin-beta-impact": {
      "id": "fin-beta-impact",
      "name": "Beta Tester Cost Impact",
      "content": "<p>Beta testers do not run up our AI bills the way paying users do.</p><p><strong>Why:</strong> Beta is structured around <strong>BYOK</strong> (bring-your-own-key). Beta users plug in their own Gemini or OpenAI keys, so the AI API costs stay on their accounts, not ours. This is intentional \u2014 it lets us run a big beta cohort without sacrificing margin.</p><p><strong>Pro-tier grants to beta users.</strong> Some beta testers (especially Founding Users) get free Pro for a stretch. That cost is mostly Stripe processing fees and RevenueCat fees on the $0 subscription \u2014 small per-user, but worth tracking in aggregate.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-financial",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "5.3"
    },
    "fin-reconciliation": {
      "id": "fin-reconciliation",
      "name": "Monthly Reconciliation",
      "content": "<p>On the first business day of each month, pull a single snapshot.</p><ol><li>Stripe revenue (gross and net after Stripe fees).</li><li>RevenueCat revenue (gross and net after Apple's 15-30% cut and RevenueCat's fee).</li><li>Total AI API spend across all providers.</li><li>Hosting + email + tooling subscriptions.</li><li>Net contribution = revenue minus cost.</li></ol><p>Log the snapshot in a spreadsheet or Notion table for trend tracking. Compare to the prior month; flag any line item that moved more than 20%.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-financial",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "5.4"
    },
    "ops-partnerships": {
      "id": "ops-partnerships",
      "name": "Strategic Partnerships Pipeline",
      "content": "<p>How active partnership conversations get tracked across two tracks: API providers and AI video tools. The detail and pitch material lives in the BizDev outline; this section is the operational pipeline.</p>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "root-ops",
      "childrenIds": [
        "partnerships-api",
        "partnerships-video",
        "partnerships-pipeline-format",
        "partnerships-review-cadence",
        "partnerships-crosslink-bizdev"
      ],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "6"
    },
    "partnerships-api": {
      "id": "partnerships-api",
      "name": "API Provider Partnerships",
      "content": "<p>Three relationships in different phases.</p><ul><li><strong>OpenAI</strong> \u2014 partnership application form pending (see the project memory note on OpenAI partnership outreach). Status: cold, application drafted.</li><li><strong>Anthropic</strong> \u2014 no formal contact yet; future Claude partnership for the Pro and Power tiers. Status: future.</li><li><strong>Google (Gemini)</strong> \u2014 ongoing operational relationship as the default Free-tier model. Status: in-discussion for credits / co-marketing.</li></ul><p>Each row needs four fields kept current: company, primary contact, last touch date, status.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-partnerships",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "6.1"
    },
    "partnerships-video": {
      "id": "partnerships-video",
      "name": "AI Video Tool Partnerships",
      "content": "<p>Seven video-AI tools in the prospect pool: Runway, MagicLight, HeyGen, Sora (OpenAI), Veo (Google), Pika, Synthesia. The strategic framing is captured in the project memory note on AI video tool partnerships \u2014 these are co-marketing and integration plays that round out IdiamPro's Outline-to-Video pipeline.</p><p>Same four-field pipeline as API providers: company, contact, last touch, status.</p><p><strong>Sequencing.</strong> Don't pursue all seven at once. Start with the two whose APIs most cleanly slot into our existing transform architecture (likely Runway and HeyGen), close those, then expand. Trying to manage seven open partnership conversations in parallel will produce zero closed deals.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-partnerships",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "6.2"
    },
    "partnerships-pipeline-format": {
      "id": "partnerships-pipeline-format",
      "name": "Pipeline Row Format",
      "content": "<p>Each partnership tracked here has the same shape:</p><ul><li><strong>Company</strong> \u2014 e.g. Runway, OpenAI</li><li><strong>Primary contact</strong> \u2014 name + email of the person on their side</li><li><strong>Last touch</strong> \u2014 date of last meaningful communication (not just an autoreply)</li><li><strong>Status</strong> \u2014 one of: <em>cold</em>, <em>in-discussion</em>, <em>agreement-drafted</em>, <em>launched</em></li><li><strong>Notes</strong> \u2014 what was promised, what's blocking, what they're waiting on, what we're waiting on</li></ul>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-partnerships",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "6.3"
    },
    "partnerships-review-cadence": {
      "id": "partnerships-review-cadence",
      "name": "Quarterly Review",
      "content": "<p>Every quarter, walk every row. For each: is the status accurate? Is the next action defined? Is the contact still the right person?</p><p>Partnerships die from drift more than from rejection. The quarterly review is the prophylactic.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-partnerships",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "6.4"
    },
    "partnerships-crosslink-bizdev": {
      "id": "partnerships-crosslink-bizdev",
      "name": "Strategic Partnerships (BizDev)",
      "content": "",
      "type": "outline-link",
      "parentId": "ops-partnerships",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": "6.5",
      "linkedOutlineId": "biz-dev-2026"
    },
    "ops-incident-response": {
      "id": "ops-incident-response",
      "name": "Incident Response",
      "content": "<p>Operational shape of how we respond when something breaks publicly. The detailed SEV ladder and runbooks live in the Legal and Compliance outline \u2014 link below.</p>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "root-ops",
      "childrenIds": [
        "incident-crosslink-legal",
        "incident-oncall",
        "incident-comms-plan"
      ],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "7"
    },
    "incident-crosslink-legal": {
      "id": "incident-crosslink-legal",
      "name": "SEV Ladder + Runbooks (Legal & Compliance)",
      "content": "",
      "type": "outline-link",
      "parentId": "ops-incident-response",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": "7.1",
      "linkedOutlineId": "idiampro-legal-compliance"
    },
    "incident-oncall": {
      "id": "incident-oncall",
      "name": "On-Call Rotation",
      "content": "<p><strong>v1: Howard is the rotation.</strong> Every incident routes to him personally, day or night.</p><p><strong>Expansion path.</strong> The first operations or engineering hire takes the primary on-call slot during business hours, with Howard remaining the escalation backstop. As headcount grows to three people, a real rotating on-call schedule kicks in (one-week shifts, primary + backup).</p><p>Until then, the practical implication is that incident readiness is bounded by Howard's availability. The runbook compensates: clear severity tagging and pre-written comms templates mean the response doesn't depend on Howard being fresh.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-incident-response",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "7.2"
    },
    "incident-comms-plan": {
      "id": "incident-comms-plan",
      "name": "Communication Plan",
      "content": "<p>Three audiences for any user-visible incident.</p><ul><li><strong>Status page.</strong> Public-facing page that lists current status, recent incidents, and resolution times. Update within 15 minutes of confirming an incident.</li><li><strong>Email to affected users.</strong> Direct email to anyone impacted: what happened, what we did, what they should do. Plain English, no jargon, no blame-shifting.</li><li><strong>Postmortem.</strong> Within five business days of resolution, publish a postmortem. What happened, why, what we changed to prevent recurrence. Public for major outages, internal-only for minor ones.</li></ul>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-incident-response",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "7.3"
    },
    "ops-compliance-privacy": {
      "id": "ops-compliance-privacy",
      "name": "Compliance & Privacy Operations",
      "content": "<p>The day-to-day work of honoring privacy law, AI consent, and data integrity.</p>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "root-ops",
      "childrenIds": [
        "comp-data-requests",
        "comp-ai-consent",
        "comp-backup-verification"
      ],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "8"
    },
    "comp-data-requests": {
      "id": "comp-data-requests",
      "name": "GDPR / CCPA Data Request Intake",
      "content": "<p>Users in jurisdictions covered by GDPR (EU) or CCPA (California) can request access to, correction of, or deletion of their personal data. The full policy and required disclosures live in the Legal and Compliance outline \u2014 link below.</p><p><strong>Operational steps.</strong> Requests come in by email to support@2ndbrainware.com (or the future privacy@ alias). Verify the requester's identity (logged-in confirmation or matching email), then fulfill within the regulatory window (30 days GDPR, 45 days CCPA).</p><p><strong>Privacy details (Legal & Compliance):</strong> see the outline link in the Incident Response section.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-compliance-privacy",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "8.1"
    },
    "comp-ai-consent": {
      "id": "comp-ai-consent",
      "name": "AI Consent Reviewer Process",
      "content": "<p>Apple Guideline 5.1.2(i) requires explicit consent before sending user data to third-party AI services. The full process is documented in the AI Data Consent section of the Legal and Compliance outline.</p><p><strong>Operational summary.</strong> Every new AI-driven feature gets a consent review before launch. The reviewer (Howard, with counsel as needed) confirms the consent prompt clearly names the destination provider, the data sent, and the user's ability to revoke.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-compliance-privacy",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "8.2"
    },
    "comp-backup-verification": {
      "id": "comp-backup-verification",
      "name": "Backup Verification Cadence",
      "content": "<p>Local outline backups in <code>~/Documents/IDM Outlines/backups/</code> rotate automatically (10 most recent per outline). Verify the rotation is working monthly: open the backups folder, confirm files exist, confirm timestamps are recent.</p><p><strong>Cloud-side backups (when sync is added):</strong> verify the cloud snapshot job runs nightly, log a successful run, and quarterly do a restore-test on a throwaway account to confirm the restore path actually works. A backup is only as good as the last verified restore.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ops-compliance-privacy",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "8.3"
    },
    "ops-env-vars-vercel-ref-2026-06-12": {
      "id": "ops-env-vars-vercel-ref-2026-06-12",
      "name": "Operational Reference \u2014 Env Vars & Vercel Controls",
      "content": "<h3>Environment Variables \u2014 what they are, why we use them, how to change them</h3>\n<p><strong>What an \"environment variable\" actually is:</strong></p>\n<p>Think of an env var as a tiny labeled box that holds a piece of configuration. The label is the NAME (like <code>SMTP_PASS</code>) and the box contains the VALUE (like your PrivateEmail password). Your IdiamPro code says \"open the box labeled SMTP_PASS and use whatever's inside.\" The actual password lives in the box at Vercel, NOT in the code. That way you can change passwords or move to a different service without touching code, and you can ship the code publicly (to GitHub) without leaking secrets.</p>\n<p><strong>Why this pattern exists:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Security.</strong> Code lives on GitHub, in your laptop's filesystem, in CI logs, in build artifacts. If the password were in the code, it'd leak constantly. The env var stays at Vercel, encrypted, only readable by the running app.</li>\n<li><strong>Environment-specific config.</strong> Production uses one database; preview deployments use another; local dev uses a third. Same code, different env vars per environment. No code changes needed to swap.</li>\n<li><strong>Hot-swappable.</strong> Change an env var in Vercel &rarr; redeploy &rarr; the code now uses the new value. Rotating a stolen API key takes 2 minutes instead of a code release.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Where env vars live in IdiamPro's setup:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Vercel dashboard</strong> &mdash; for production and preview. Encrypted at rest. Only you can view them.</li>\n<li><strong><code>.env.local</code> on your laptop</strong> &mdash; for local development (Electron + dev server). Plaintext file on your machine. Git ignores it (never gets committed).</li>\n<li><strong><code>.env.example</code> in the codebase</strong> &mdash; documents which env vars exist, with empty values. Safe to commit because no actual secrets.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong><code>NEXT_PUBLIC_</code> prefix &mdash; important distinction:</strong></p>\n<p>Some env vars have a <code>NEXT_PUBLIC_</code> prefix (like <code>NEXT_PUBLIC_CLERK_PUBLISHABLE_KEY</code>). That prefix tells Next.js \"bake this value into the JavaScript that gets shipped to browsers.\" So anyone viewing the page source can see it. We only use <code>NEXT_PUBLIC_</code> for values that are SAFE to be public &mdash; usually \"publishable keys\" that identify the app without granting access. The \"secret key\" twins (like <code>CLERK_SECRET_KEY</code>) stay server-only &mdash; never sent to the browser.</p>\n<h3>The actual env vars IdiamPro uses</h3>\n<table>\n<thead><tr><th>Env var</th><th>What it does</th><th>Service it talks to</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><code>SMTP_HOST</code></td><td>Server to send email through</td><td>PrivateEmail (mail.privateemail.com)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>SMTP_PORT</code></td><td>Network port for SMTP (465 = TLS encrypted)</td><td>PrivateEmail</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>SMTP_USER</code></td><td>Mailbox to authenticate as</td><td>PrivateEmail</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>SMTP_PASS</code></td><td>Password for that mailbox</td><td>PrivateEmail</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>EMAIL_FROM</code></td><td>Address shown as sender on outgoing emails</td><td>(optional &mdash; defaults to SMTP_USER)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>EMAIL_TO_ADMIN</code></td><td>Where new-applicant notifications get sent</td><td>(optional &mdash; defaults to howard@2ndbrainware.com)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>KV_REST_API_URL</code></td><td>Where the Upstash database lives</td><td>Upstash (auto-set by Vercel integration)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>KV_REST_API_TOKEN</code></td><td>Password for the database</td><td>Upstash (auto-set)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>GEMINI_API_KEY</code></td><td>Lets the app call Google's Gemini AI</td><td>Google</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>RESEND_API_KEY</code></td><td>Legacy fallback (not currently used)</td><td>Resend</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>NEXT_PUBLIC_CLERK_PUBLISHABLE_KEY</code></td><td>Public ID for auth &mdash; visible to browser</td><td>Clerk (not yet set)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>CLERK_SECRET_KEY</code></td><td>Server-only auth secret</td><td>Clerk (not yet set)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>STRIPE_SECRET_KEY</code></td><td>Lets the app process web payments</td><td>Stripe (not yet set)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>REVENUECAT_*</code></td><td>iOS in-app purchase coordination</td><td>RevenueCat (not yet set)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>SENTRY_DSN</code> / <code>NEXT_PUBLIC_SENTRY_DSN</code></td><td>Where crash reports go</td><td>Sentry (not yet set)</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>The blanks at the bottom are remaining setup items.</p>\n<p><strong>Stub-safe pattern:</strong> every env var IdiamPro uses is OPTIONAL. If it's missing, the related feature silently no-ops with a log line &mdash; nothing crashes. That's why we could ship the SMTP swap before the password was set, and why missing Clerk keys gracefully hide the signup form instead of breaking the page.</p>\n<h3>Vercel &mdash; what it is and how it's configured</h3>\n<p><strong>What Vercel is:</strong></p>\n<p>Vercel runs the website on a global network of computers. When someone types 2ndbrainware.com, the nearest Vercel computer serves them the page in milliseconds. Vercel ALSO runs \"serverless functions\" &mdash; small programs that respond to API requests (like signup form submissions) on demand, without managing servers.</p>\n<p><strong>Key Vercel concepts:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Project</strong> &mdash; the IdiamPro app at Vercel. Has a name (<code>idiam-pro</code>), an ID, settings.</li>\n<li><strong>Deployment</strong> &mdash; one specific snapshot of the code. Every git push creates a new deployment. The latest one is \"Production\"; older ones are kept around for rollback.</li>\n<li><strong>Environments</strong> &mdash; Production, Preview (for branch previews), Development. Env vars can differ per environment.</li>\n<li><strong>Domains</strong> &mdash; human-readable names pointed at the project. Currently <code>2ndbrainware.com</code>, <code>www.2ndbrainware.com</code>, and the default <code>idiam-pro.vercel.app</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>Storage</strong> &mdash; managed databases attached to the project. Currently: one Upstash KV.</li>\n<li><strong>Logs</strong> &mdash; every request and every function invocation gets logged. Visible in real time.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>How configuration flows:</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Change something in the Vercel dashboard (add env var, add domain, etc.)</li>\n<li>Vercel says \"needs a redeploy\"</li>\n<li>Either push code OR click \"Redeploy\" on the latest deployment</li>\n<li>Vercel builds a fresh deployment with the new config</li>\n<li>Vercel automatically points 2ndbrainware.com at the new deployment</li>\n<li>Old deployment stays around but no longer receives traffic &mdash; one-click rollback available</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>How to alter things</h3>\n<p><strong>Change an env var value (e.g., rotate the SMTP password):</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Go to https://vercel.com/howard-jachters-projects/idiam-pro/settings/environment-variables</li>\n<li>Find the row (e.g. <code>SMTP_PASS</code>), click the three-dot menu, click Edit</li>\n<li>Type the new value, click Save</li>\n<li>Click \"Redeploy\" on the prompt (or trigger one from Deployments page)</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Add a new env var:</strong> Same page, scroll to bottom, type name + value, pick which environments it applies to, Save, redeploy.</p>\n<p><strong>Change which domain points at production:</strong> https://vercel.com/howard-jachters-projects/idiam-pro/domains</p>\n<p><strong>Roll back to a previous deployment:</strong> https://vercel.com/howard-jachters-projects/idiam-pro/deployments &mdash; find an earlier \"Ready\" deployment, three-dot menu, \"Promote to Production\". Live traffic moves to it within seconds.</p>\n<p><strong>Trigger a manual redeploy:</strong> Same Deployments page, three-dot on the latest, \"Redeploy\".</p>\n<p><strong>Open the database to inspect data:</strong> https://vercel.com/howard-jachters-projects/idiam-pro/stores &mdash; click the Upstash database, then \"Open in Upstash\" &mdash; browser-based console for inspecting records.</p>\n<p><strong>Check logs when something fails:</strong> https://vercel.com/howard-jachters-projects/idiam-pro/logs &mdash; real-time stream of every request and error. Filter by function (e.g., <code>/api/applicants/apply</code>) to debug specific features.</p>\n<h3>Technical glossary</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>DNS</strong> &mdash; the phone book of the internet. Maps human-readable names (2ndbrainware.com) to machine IPs.</li>\n<li><strong>MX record</strong> &mdash; the DNS entry that says \"send mail for this domain to this server.\"</li>\n<li><strong>A record</strong> &mdash; the DNS entry that says \"send web traffic for this domain to this IP.\"</li>\n<li><strong>CNAME</strong> &mdash; DNS entry that says \"this name points to that other name.\"</li>\n<li><strong>SMTP</strong> &mdash; Simple Mail Transfer Protocol. The 1980s-era language email servers use to hand mail to each other.</li>\n<li><strong>TLS / SSL</strong> &mdash; encryption for data in transit. Why URLs start with HTTPS instead of HTTP.</li>\n<li><strong>API endpoint</strong> &mdash; a URL on the server that accepts data and returns a response (e.g., <code>/api/applicants/apply</code>).</li>\n<li><strong>Serverless function</strong> &mdash; a small program that runs on-demand on Vercel's computers. No idle server cost.</li>\n<li><strong>KV (Key-Value) store</strong> &mdash; a database that stores data by lookup key. Simpler than SQL, faster for our use case.</li>\n<li><strong>Webhook</strong> &mdash; an external service (Clerk, Stripe) calling OUR API to tell us something happened.</li>\n<li><strong>Cron job</strong> &mdash; a scheduled task. The feedback reminder runs every day at noon via Vercel cron.</li>\n<li><strong>Env-gated / stub-safe</strong> &mdash; code that no-ops when its env vars aren't set, instead of crashing.</li>\n<li><strong>Idempotent</strong> &mdash; an operation safe to repeat &mdash; running it twice has the same effect as once. The welcome email is idempotent.</li>\n<li><strong>DKIM / SPF / DMARC</strong> &mdash; DNS-based email authentication. DKIM signs each email; SPF says \"these servers are allowed to send mail for this domain\"; DMARC tells receiving servers what to do if SPF/DKIM fails.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><em>Set up 2026-06-11 / 2026-06-12 during the email + storage setup session.</em></p>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "root-ops",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": ""
    }
  },
  "lastModified": 1781164800000,
  "createdAt": 1781164800000
}